Quynh’s Media Consumption in 2024

Quynh Phung

I’ve consumed a lot of media in the last twelve months, and this project attempts to organize, summarize, and visualize the data I tracked in 2024. I only track movies, albums, and books, but that represents the vast majority of my media consumption. I rate each piece of media out of 20 because it provides the perfect balance in which every integer represents a meaningful difference in quality.

Albums

In 2024, I listened to 85 studio albums for the first time, compared to 50 in 2023, the first year I started tracking albums. Of those 85 albums, 31 were released in 2024. This totaled over 61 hours of new music, with the longest album, Taylor Swift’s The Tortured Poet’s Department clocking in at over 2 hours long, and the shortest, Martin Luke Brown’s damn, look at the view! coming in at less than 25 minutes. The average album length was 43.44 minutes. This table contains all the data I track for the albums I listen to. The table is sorted by default by my personal ranking of all 85 albums, but you can sort and filter by any of the columns, search the table, or change the number of entries displayed on each page.

The distribution of my ratings looks like:

This looks like a skewed normal distribution, with an average rating of 15.47 and a standard deviation of 2.82. Presumably, the distribution of ratings for all the albums in the world would not be skewed, but my personal ratings fall mostly in the 15-18 range because I don’t often challenge myself to listen to music I might not like.

We can also look at the number of albums I listened to in each month:

Of the three types of media I track, music is the most resilient to outside factors in my life, because I can and do listen to music while performing other activities. Even from January through April when I was finishing grad school, I listened to new albums at a relatively consistent rate, other than March when I entered my first jazz funk fusion era, and even after graduating in May, the rate never rose above 11 albums in a month.

We can also examine whether an album’s length has any bearing on my rating,

which reveals a slight trend: in general I tend to enjoy shorter albums.

We can also examine the artists I listened to multiple albums from:

which pretty much shows all my favorite artists that I discovered in 2024.

The other data point that would be interesting to draw conclusions from is the genre of each album; however, that is much more complicated to track as the lines between genres are blurry, and I assigned genre names rather arbitrarily. This data point would require a more robust treatment than I am prepared to spend time on at this point. This applies to book and movie genres as well.

Movies

In 2024, I watched 120 movies for the first time. This is the first year I’ve tracked my movies watched. This totaled over 215 hours of movies, with the longest movie, Satantango, clocking in at over 7 hours, and the shortest short film, “Just a Minute,” clocking in at 3 minutes. The average movie length was 107.69 minutes. This table contains all the data I track for movies:

The distribution of ratings for movies looks like:

Which again, looks like a skewed normal distribution, with an average rating of 13.84 and a standard deviation of 4.12. The mean is lower and the standard deviation is higher than my distribution for albums, probably because I have a higher tolerance to watch mid-to-bad movies and because of the larger sample size.

Looking at the number of movies I watched in each month throughout the year:

My movie watching habits are much less resilient than my music listening, as evidenced by the dearth of movies watched while I was finishing grad school, the big jump to 15-25 movies per month over the summer, at some points close to a movie every day, and the sharp drop off in October when I moved to Ohio.

The graph of release years for each movie reveals less info than it did for albums:

And similarly for the movie length,

An interesting stat to calculate is the difference between my rating and Letterboxd’s rating, which is summarized in this table:

The most positive rating differences were for movies I enjoyed that were mid to most of the Letterboxd audience, including two Dakota Johnson movies, Daddio and Am I OK?. The most negative differences were mostly movies that I greatly disliked, including bad movies like Eat Pray Love, Not Another Teen Movie, and Mean Girls, and problematic movies like Cloud Atlas, Babyteeth, and Promising Young Woman.

We can also look at all the directors I watched multiple movies from:

This list is topped by two of my favorite directors, Emma Seligman and Celine Sciamma, who have three movies including one short film each. They are joined in the 3 movies group by Ti West due to his X-Pearl-MaXXXine trilogy, of which Pearl is doing most of the heavy lifting for his rating. The dubious distinction of last place on this list goes to Robert Schwentke, who directed Insurgent and Allegiant from the Divergent film trilogy.

Books

In 2024, I read 64 books for the first time, compared to 6 in 2023 and 25 in 2022, the first year I started tracking books. This totaled 24475 pages read, with the longest two books, Samantha Shannon’s The Priory of the Orange Tree and A Day of Fallen Night clocking in at 845 and 868 pages each, and the shortest being John Steinbeck’s novella “The Pearl” at 96 pages. This table contains the rankings and data for all 64 books:

The distribution of ratings for the books looks like:

which again looks like a skewed normal distribution, with an average rating of 13.23 and a standard deviation of 5.34. The mean is even lower and the standard deviation higher than the distribution of my movie ratings, but the mode for books is the highest of all three media types, 17 and 18. I believe this is because books are the most involved of the three media types, so I am less likely to have ambivalent feelings and more likely to feel strongly for or against the book because I spent so much time on it. I am also much more willing to read really bad books than listen to bad albums or watch bad movies.

Looking at the number of books I read in each month:

Books are the least resilient type of media to outside factors. I didn’t finish a single book the entire time I was finishing grad school, working on Mary Boyce’s Zoroastrians for the entire four months. The rate of book reading jumped significantly to finishing a book about every other day during my months in Mahomet in August and September, and than came straight back down in October and November when I moved to Huron, jumping up again when I had time to read over the holidays in December.

The publication date seems to have little correlation with my enjoyment of a book:

and same with the length of a book:

Similarly to movies, we can calculate the difference between my rating and Goodreads’ rating:

Again, the most positive differences were from books I loved, including several sapphic romances like Kiss Her Once for Me, 6 Times We Almost Kissed [And One Time We Did], Some Girls Do, and Imogen, Obviously. On the other hand, the most negative differences were books I really hated, bottoming out with my two least favorite books of all time, On the Road and Fourth Wing.

Examining again the authors I read multiple books from:

Leigh Bardugo comes in with the most books due to both her Shadow and Bones and Six of Crows series, while the first three books of A Court of Thorns and Roses puts Sarah J. Maas in second place in terms of number of books, although she is very much dead last in rating. Samantha Shannon’s Priory world is easily my favorite of the repeat authors, followed by Victoria Schwab’s Villains series.

This was a lot of fun, and I will definitely be doing this again for 2025. My goal for this year is 75 books, 100 albums, and 150 movies. Let me know if you have any ideas for further data visualizations or would like to see any particular stats. If you have any comments on any of the media I consumed in 2024, I’d also love to hear them. And finally, I am always taking recommendations for any movies, books, or albums you think I might like.
